segments.text: because the Texas and Southwestern cattle raisers in their executive committee say, well, you know, these youngsters have had eight years of college, but now they should know everything.
Yeah, right.
Oh, sure.
Okay, so that's as far as our pressures on the clinical.
How about the pressures on the research, which you said was another one of the aims that you wanted to improve?
Well, as I mentioned,
When I came here, and you've interviewed Dr. Price, and you mentioned that he left you with a perception of the growth of the college.
And it had been phenomenal.
And the physical plant had grown not as much as it should have, but certainly it had grown substantially.
And the numbers of students had become overwhelming.
biggest in the nation.
We were on an accelerated program where they finished in three years.
We had started a undergraduate program in biomedical science.
And so we had students running out of our ears.
And in this complex at one time or another, we had 1,500, 1,600 students, which is unbelievable for a professional school.
Most veterinary schools think in terms of
working with only 500 or 600 students at best.
So our teaching program was enormous.
Our faculty, many of them were spending 16, 18, 20 hours a week actually in laboratory lecture facing students.
My goodness.
That didn't leave any time for us.
It doesn't.
That's right.
So what we had was a teaching mill.
We had a few professors that had joint appointments with the Agricultural Experiment Station, or something like that, where there may be 50% research that could find a little time to do research.
But 80% of our faculty were doing none, or very little.
And we were so oriented toward the teaching program that it was very difficult to find time for the faculty
And even more difficult than finding time was changing the orientation, changing the direction of the faculty.
They had gotten into a habit.
They had gotten into a rut.
And that trimester system just rolled over like a wheel in a rut.
And you'd turn over three times in a year.
And then you'd just keep right down that rut.
And I remember one of my first eye-opening experiences
came to Texas A&M.
I had a young faculty member that, probably 35 years old, and he had just come back from Iowa State with a new PhD two or three years before, a few years before.
And one night at a social function, I asked him, I said, how can we shift the emphasis of our program and get more research going?
And he looked me straight in the eye and said, why should I?
Or why should we?
Now I knew I had a problem.
Because, you know, that never dawned on me that a young man of that background and orientation would question why we should need more research.
But, you know, he looked me in the eye and said, why should we?
And that's when I knew I had a problem.
Because what he was really reflecting was the attitude of a lot of the faculty.
So it's been...
hard battle.
Dr. Price made a noble effort to move this before he stepped out when he brought Dr. Maurer here.
He had done a noble effort and he had jarred a few cracks open
But, boy, it was still a long way to go.
And it has still been a long way to go, and it still is.
And what steps have you taken?
I mean, have you given them some release time or maybe more sabbatical-type time?
Because research just consumes so much time.
Well, Terry, I guess the thing is, I've done all I could, but the biggest nightmare has been...
overcoming attitudes, overcoming attitudes of faculty and overcoming attitudes of department heads.

We fight like mad to keep all our positions filled, because it's only by keeping positions filled that we are able to have time to give faculty members relief for a semester, like those that are in the block training system in the clinic.
What we try to do is give every faculty member over three blocks of the 10 off, that's 15 weeks a year, that they're free of teaching.
So that gives them some time for scholarship or self-study, self-improvement.
And if they can get some research in there, fine.
But we've tried, like everything, to add a few new positions.
It's been tough to add positions.
And the difficulty there is this.
We're under the formula and under all the teaching load reports, and we can only justify new positions by student enrollment, really, and student credit hours taught.
So if you do that, then you sort of catch 22.
Yeah, exactly.
You're right where you started again.
So it's been a difficult thing.
It's a problem with the legislature, then.
Yeah, the Texas legislature, as you well know, and I'm sure you hear this all the time.
They really don't believe in research.
No.
And, for instance, the organized research, you know how little they fund that and how repeatedly they've quacked at it and tried to cut it out.
And all that is is just a little seed money for young teachers to try to get them started.
And it
the best investment that state could make.

But the organized research is a stepchild and it, you know, they get up over there and they talk about how some of those dollars have been used or some professor could study the color of lizard coats and tree lizard or something, you know, and they think they're being funny because they don't understand research and they don't understand what it means.
So

The only approaches that we've had a little luck with, and I think where we've made the most progress, is by recruiting young faculty from other institutions that know the importance of it and who are willing to do the extra work, walk the extra mile to get started.
And once you can ever get the start where you can get some sponsored research money and you can relieve
a part of a person's salary to leave them on to a research program.
Then you can build from that, and you relieve their faculty time.
You let you hire some other teachers to do the teaching.
And this is how the College of Engineering has been able to do it, and some others that have been more successful than we have.
College of Geoscience has been able to do it.
Part of me, they have sponsors where they can get research money better than we can.
We're fighting a tough market.
right now.
It would have been so much easier to have done it in the 60s.
When there was more money.
When there was more research money.
But for whatever reason, and I don't know what the political pressures were on Dr. Price and the executive committee in the 60s, but for whatever reason they decided to expand enrollment.
And there was a great pressure to expand enrollment.
Whatever there was, they did that and they didn't push research.
for whatever reason.
And so you'd consider yourself the first dean then to push research?
Oh, I don't know, because Dr. Price... Emphasize, we'll say.
I pushed a little harder than Dr. Price did.
Dr. Price was trying, you know.
I sure want to be fair, because he began to, he set the rules in motion, and he was trying.
Perhaps I'm the first one that's made more fuss about it, trying...
Some of the faculty members say it's all I care about.
That's not right.
I've tried to bring balance.
I believe in strong teaching as much as anybody, but I've tried to bring balance to the program, try to improve our clinical training program, try to improve our research effort without
damaging our teaching program.
How many hours a week, or what's the course load for an assistant professor, the average professor?
Well, it varies all over the place because our teaching is so much different from, say, history or sociology or political science or engineering even, although it's more like engineering.
We have so many lab hours.
So much of our teaching has to be done, especially in the clinical area,
in small, very narrow student-teacher ratios, one to three, one to four.
And that's expensive and time-consuming.
Because our profession is esoteric.
The graduate immediately enters a field of private practice, and the average client doesn't really know what a veterinary knows
what his training is, just like medicine.
And so there's a great demand for quality control.
And that's what we've been able to do in American schools that they don't do in some other places like Mexico or Italy or so forth when they'll take classes of 500 students and lecture to them.
They don't know whether they've learned anything or not.
We have the very...

Narrow student-teacher ratios in the clinical sciences where the instructor works closely with the individual to know whether they can do surgery or not, whether they can operate a radiological equipment, whether they can operate an anesthetic machine without killing the patient.
And these things have to be done almost like a one-on-one, one-on-three, something like that.
And so I'd say try to get back to your question.
I feel that it, and I think it varies a great deal.
Yes, ma'am.
Excuse me.
Your 11 o'clock appointment's here.
All right.
Thank you.
I feel that it varies, but somehow a teacher shouldn't have to face students, whether in the lecture room or the lavatory or on rounds in the clinic.
He or she shouldn't have to face students more than about 15 hours a week, whatever system, whatever shape.
But now I know a lot of our clinicians do.
Some of them are 20, 25 hours a week.
That must be draining.
It is, very draining, very draining.
It's just too much.
They need time for reflection, time for thought, time for preparation, time for study, time for self-development.
It's so hard to do.
We've tried to improve some by bringing in the residency training program.
We bring the young veterinarians in for two and three years of postgraduate training.
And when did you start this program?
We started in about 75.
And now we have about 20 students in residency training.
And they give some of the clinicians, the senior staff, some relief.
And you bring these men and women right out of the field then?
Well, they either come through a one-year internship, or they may take their internship in a private practice.
But when we bring them into residency, they've had at least one year experience post-graduate.
And then they go into a residency program of two or three years.
And this moves them towards certification in one of the 12 colleges, specialty colleges, like surgery, internal medicine, radiology, pathology, and on and on.
That's a great idea.
Was that your idea, basically?
Well, it was my idea to try to build a residency program because we didn't have one when I came here.
But I can't claim, you know, I couldn't claim ID for the residency program because they started in other schools before.
Oh, I see.
That sounds like, that's more like a medical doctor residency training.
Pattern after pattern, very similar.
And a way to, so the young person can specialize.
Yeah.
It's been another way to push back the curtain of ignorance into clinical sciences.
Mm-hmm.
uh, as different from the traditional graduate program, the master's and PhD research program.
This is more oriented toward the service or clinical program.
But we've, uh, we felt that they've helped us.
It's helped us a great deal in two respects.

One, it's taken some weight off of the senior faculty, uh, facing students, as I mentioned, so many hours a day, but also those young minds are the most progressive, probing young minds in the, in the field.
And they stimulate the older professor, too.
So it's been good.
I think it would be tremendous.
I think it's an excellent idea.
It's been helpful, very helpful.
And how many a year do we have?
Well, we have about, let's see, I think about 22 residents right now.
No, no, 22 interns and residents.
We have four interns and the rest are residents, so 22 altogether.
And we graduate each year about, there'll be about three in the large animal finish and about three in small.
Each year we'll have two to three finish.
And they go on to become faculty members somewhere else or they may go into specialty practice.
They get their boards in a couple of years after they finish here.
Sounds like an excellent.
Do we have a couple more minutes or do we have to quit?
Yeah.
If you can, or we could... No, I just want to ask you about those residency training, the clinical aspects, sound like a couple of your accomplishments.
What else would you consider your accomplishments?
And then let's talk about some things that you might consider your shortcomings as the dean.
Well, I guess strengthening the clinical program has been my...
I guess something I could point to that, well, I didn't do.
I've helped and aided to accomplish.
Dean never does anything really.
He just creates the environment to get it done.
Put some weight behind it.
Yeah.
Leans.
There's leans and lashes a little in there.
That has been one.
I think I would have to.

I would say that I have been able to build better bridges with the state, the industry, and so forth by working hard to build the bridges with the commodity groups, industrial groups, by our advisory board development.
We've moved ahead in development, private sector creation of a development council.
We've improved our research, I think, some.
And I'll put that on the negative side, too, because not enough.
But I think we've made some progress.
We had pretty good progress with the Institute of Comparative Medicine, a joint effort with Baylor until the governor shot it down two years ago.
But that allowed us to improve our research efforts and bring some faculty in we couldn't have brought in otherwise.
Was it too expensive for Clements?
Oh, the governor just got it because he had run on a political promise of cutting taxes, and it was vulnerable to his red pencil.
So he cut it out in 1979.
It was another one of those 5% waste things.
Yeah.
He ran on Proposition 13 in Texas, where we had the lowest tax base in the country.
But that's part of this business.
You win some and you lose some.
But I think we have improved our research effort to some degree and had some success with it.
I think we've built a better bridge with the industry.
Certainly not what I'd like to see, but I think it's a lot better.
I think we're working better with the
especially with the Texas Agricultural Experiment Station.
And we've developed some interdepartmental research programs in the college, like the one we have going with brucellosis, which is a substantial name, a good effort, giving us national visibility.
So, yes, I think we've been able to improve our clinical program, and overall we've improved our research program.
And those were two
goals that I came here with.
And I think we've been fairly successful.
I guess I also saw after coming here that we needed to move away from the accelerated program.
So we're moving away from that.
I think that was an accomplishment for Dr. Price in early 60s.
On the flip side of the coin, I think it's almost an accomplishment
for me or for our current administration, executive committee, to go back because I think it had outlived its usefulness.
So in other words, we're keeping a flexible administration.
That's right.
In terms of the times.
Oh, yes.
No way to get a rigid one.
We have to respond to changing times and changing needs.
How about shortcomings?
Things that you wanted to do, but you, well, you said research, for example.
You want to get more research time, and you want to have more people doing research.
I want to see the research program better.
I want to see more people here with national visibility in research.
I think we have a state, the economy, the resources.
We ought to be stronger in research.
I hope that in the next few years, we can keep moving in that way.
step out of here in a few years, I can at least feel that it's moving in that direction.
So I want to see the research effort build and do much better than it has so far.
I still would like to see us improve our program and food animal medicine more than we have.
And we have to do that.
We have to get some better leadership there.
We have a number of people getting on toward retirement, maybe with their
When those people step down, we can find some stronger leadership in food animal medicine.
It's been tough because the faculty there is getting a bit old.
Other areas that I think there's a need for curricular change, a substantial curriculum change, and I don't know.
We've had a curriculum committee.
We've pushed them pretty hard into it.
in-depth study for the last three years now.
And at times, it seems like maybe we're making some breakthrough.
But we need change in two areas.
Number one, a curriculum more attuned to the needs of the last decade of this century and the first decade of the next century.
And also, we need improvement in our teaching methods.
We're still kind of obsolete there.
I'm hoping that shifting back to a four-year curriculum, maybe getting some time for people to have some time in the summers to work on instructional methods will help.
And that's one of the reasons I would have to say I fought hard to leave the accelerated program.
And I say that in all due respect to Dr. Price and the people that in the early 1960s saw fit to go that way.
But I sure saw fit to go out.
And it's been tough to do that.
It hadn't been easy.
We need more time for reflection and for research, then.
I'm not sure I'm following your question.
More time for reflection, for teaching methods, and staying on top of your discipline and your subject matter, more time to read the material, and more time for the professor to do the research.
Oh, yeah.
Those are the reasons, I think.
We're shifting the focus now.
Yeah.
Those are the justifications, I think.
Now, if you had to rank Texas A&M, I know it's the largest student body as far as the largest vet school in the country.
If you had to rank it along teaching and research, how would you rank it?
My students come in all the time.
I have a lot of pre-vet students.
They're excellent students.
They come in there.
They're eager.
They want to know how to improve in my course.
It's a pleasure to have them.
And they always want to know, tell me everything you know about the vet school.
So I want to get it firsthand.
They say, I know it's the largest.
I don't know how a professional, though, would rank it.
Well, we're not, in my opinion, we're not the top school by a substantial number.
And we're not the bottom by a hell of a long way either.
I guess, and I know they have some weaknesses just like we do, I guess I'd rank California Davis top overall.
In research, then I'd put Cornell probably second.
Cornell might even be first in research.
in the orientation toward comparative medicine, orientation with human medicine, and from a strictly overall scholarship, I'd rank University of Pennsylvania second or third.
So Davis, Pennsylvania, and Cornell, some combination.
Although I think our clinical program and our teaching program might be stronger than Cornell.
I'd place us in
right below that tier.
The next group of three or four.
I'd place Texas A&M, Ohio State, Iowa State in that tier.
I could point out areas that we're probably stronger than any.
Okay, would you do that for me?
Well, I really think from the standpoint of our students being ready to move into the business world
or to the professional world of practice to go to work the day they graduate, I really think our graduates may be at the top of the whole box.
But from the standpoint of the in-depth education, I'm not sure that's true.
And I think we're still suffering from the effects of the accelerated program.
I would hope that in four to five years that we could say that our overall teaching, research, and service, judged on all three, that we'd be either tops or among the top three.
And I don't think that's unreasonable.
Some people might say we're there now.
I don't think we are.
Because I think we're still lopsided.
But I think it's, see, we'll be back on a four-year curriculum.
And I think from there, within another three years, if we can keep getting the resources that we need, we can be among the top three.
Because right now, I know Cornell's having problems keeping their standard.
They still have the strong research program.
They have a much smaller school than we do.
They only take 75 students.
And so as a result, maybe they are able to give a little more in-depth training than we are.
But I think we can be a moment.
Sounds like you have your challenges for the future.
Well, are there some other issues?
These are basically the things that I wanted to talk about.
Are there other issues that you might want to explore in a later interview?
Or do you think we should close it at this?
Are there other things that you'd like to say?
Up ahead, I don't know, Terry.
I don't know.
I couldn't say there are.
Well, maybe you should read the transcript.
All right.
Well, thanks a lot.
If after, when you're all ready to close, you have other questions, well, I'd be glad to try to answer them or chat with you about them.
But I don't know of anything else.
One last thing, and that is, why are more students, why is vet school, entrance into vet school, more competitive today than medical school?
It seems like the last 10 years, maybe even longer, there's just been this great surge of students who want to go to vet school.
It has dropped off some.
It is beginning to drop off.
But you're right.
I'm not sure.
I've thought about that a lot and theorized.
I have some
theories about it.
I think that we had a reaction from the 68 to 70 time, when all the young people were striving for relevancy, trying to see some value to why they were working, to life.
They tried to turn back to nature.
They swarmed into courses like what
diseases of fish and wildlife when there weren't any jobs there.
There weren't enough jobs there.
As a result of books like James Harold's All Creatures Great and Small, I could see maybe some basic values in being able to administer to the health and well-being of animals.
And then, of course,
That almost assumed an equal rank with medicine for a lot of young people.
Many of them sort of were turned off to medicine because they had the image that medicine was so monetary and so financially oriented.
Well, I don't know.
But of course, there were only, at that time, 18 veterinary schools, and there were 120 medical schools.
It was harder to get into veterinary schools because of the numbers.
And so that built an artificial situation that we've had to deal with.
And we talked about it earlier this morning.
But that was a factor.
I guess that was part of it.
So now you think that it's on the decline?
It's tipping away from that.
Many states, the numbers have dropped off.
Marketly, we haven't seen much drop off.
On the other hand, we haven't had any increase either.
In fact, I guess we have about 100 less applicants now than we did at the peak.
But still, you have about 600 who are qualified.
About 500 now.
Oh, so it has dropped down.
Yeah, from 600.
Slightly under five now, where one time it was six.
So we're down 100.
Do you see this as a tendency for the future?
Do you think it's going to drop down a little bit more?
I would anticipate that it will.
I think it will.
and everything goes in cycles.
Sure, sure.
Well, thanks a lot for this interview.
I really appreciate it.
My pleasure.
